x, England":"Singleton, Sussex, England","Arundel Castle, Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel Castle, Sussex, England"},"en":{"circa 1445–25 October 1524":"1445–25 October 1524","1445–1524":"1445–1524","1450–1524":"1450–1524","1454–1538":"1454–1538","1458–Female":"1458–Deceased","1449–1491":"1449–1491","1476–Female":"1476–Deceased","1417–1487":"1417–1487","1423–1462":"1423–1462","25 October 1524":"25 October 1524","1462":"1462","1450":"1450","1491":"1491","15 December 1487":"15 December 1487","1458":"1458","1524":"1524","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1476":"1476","1454":"1454","6 March 1491":"6 March 1491","about 1476":"about 1476","circa 1445":"1445","1417":"1417","1538":"1538","before 9 September 1462":"before 9 September 1462","1449":"1449","Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Singleton, Sussex, England":"Singleton, Sussex, England","Arundel Castle, Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel Castle, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzAlan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name  <i>Alan</i> (  see  Allen  ), ‘son of  <i>Alan</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]},{"name":"Allen","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Alain</i>, <i>Alein</i> (Old Breton <i>Alan</i>), from a Celtic personal name of great antiquity and obscurity. In England the personal name is now usually spelled <i>Alan</i>, the surname <i>Allen</i>; in Scotland the surname is more often <i>Allan</i>. From 1139 it was common in Scotland, where the surname also derives from Gaelic <i>Ailéne</i>, <i>Ailín</i>, from <i>ail</i> ‘rock’. The present-day frequency of the surname Allen in England and Ireland is partly accounted for by the popularity of the personal name among Breton followers of William the Conqueror, by whom it was imported first to Britain and then to Ireland. Saint Alan(us) was a 5th-century bishop of Quimper, who was a cult figure in medieval Brittany. Another Saint Al(l)an was a Cornish or Breton saint of the 6th century, to whom a church in Cornwall is dedicated.","English: occasionally perhaps from the rare Middle English femaje personal name <i>Aline</i> (Old French <i>Adaline</i>, <i>Aaline</i>), a pet form of ancient Germanic names in <i>Adal-</i>, especially <i>Adalheidis</i> (see   Allis  ).","French: variant of   Allain  , a cognate of 1 above, and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":10,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William FitzAlan was born in 1445, in Arundel Castle, Sussex, England, his father, William FitzAlan, was 28 and his mother, Joan Neville, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Haughstone. He died on 25 October 1524, in Singleton, Sussex, England, at the age of 79."},"et":{"circa 1445–25 October 1524":"1445–25. oktoober 1524","1445–1524":"1445–1524","1450–1524":"1450–1524","1454–1538":"1454–1538","1458–Female":"1458–Surnud","1449–1491":"1449–1491","1476–Female":"1476–Surnud","1417–1487":"1417–1487","1423–1462":"1423–1462","25 October 1524":"25. oktoober 1524","1462":"1462","1450":"1450","1491":"1491","15 December 1487":"15. detsember 1487","1458":"1458","1524":"1524","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1476":"1476","1454":"1454","6 March 1491":"6. märts 1491","about 1476":"umbes 1476","circa 1445":"1445","1417":"1417","1538":"1538","before 9 September 1462":"enne 9. septembrit 1462","1449":"1449","Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Singleton, Sussex, England":"Singleton, Sussex, England","Arundel Castle, Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel Castle, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"circa 1445–25 October 1524":"1445–25. lokakuuta 1524","1445–1524":"1445–1524","1450–1524":"1450–1524","1454–1538":"1454–1538","1458–Female":"1458–Kuollut","1449–1491":"1449–1491","1476–Female":"1476–Kuollut","1417–1487":"1417–1487","1423–1462":"1423–1462","25 October 1524":"25. lokakuuta 1524","1462"